To handle the case where no match is found and return `undefined` instead of causing an error, you can add a check to see if `user` is `undefined` before trying to access `user.users.id`. Here's how you can modify your function:

```typescript
async verifyUserHasRole({ userId, name }: { userId: number; name: string }): Promise<number | undefined> {
    const [user] = await this.db
      .select()
      .from(users)
      .leftJoin(rolesToUsers, eq(users.id, rolesToUsers.userId))
      .leftJoin(roles, eq(rolesToUsers.roleId, roles.id))
      .where(and(eq(users.id, userId), eq(roles.name, name)));

    if (!user) {
        return undefined;
    }

    return user.users.id;
}
```

In this code, the `if (!user)` check ensures that if no matching user is found, the function will return `undefined` instead of trying to access `user.users.id` and causing an error.
